{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_moser_ver01/data/sn85025371/00542867322/1930091101/0716.xml":{"full_text":"The Clarke Courier\nR. N. Dorsey, Publisher\nEstablished in ItMib by Capl. Win. X. i\nNelson; owned mid edited by the\nlate Joint O. Crown and Joseph\nVV. Crown for more; Ilian !I3 years.\nEntered at the Po.slollice at Berry\nville.'Vn., asi second-class mail mat\nter.\nPer If ear In Advance\nROBERT POWEL PAGE\nOnly arstocrats signed their names\nto the Golden Book of Venice, and\nthen only when they had come up\nout of the ruck and established\nthemselves in the world.\nWe Virginians are proud of our\nold homes and prouder yet of the\nnames that have adorned them.\nSome of these names, of men and\nErfglish language is spoken, and will\nbe known for all time.\nThere are others, not so widely\nknown to the world at large, that\nhold a place in the mjnds and hearts\nof Virginians as to be almost sacred,\nand two of those are Page and Sara\ntoga.\nThe man, the last great gentleman\nof his community and generation,\nthe house the most fitting for his\npersonality.\nAs far as the Millwood Community\nis concerned its Golden Book has re\nceived its last entry. Robert Powel\nPage, Soldier of Lee and Virginia\ngentleman of a day that is no more,\nhas been called to join the Army of\nNorthern Virginia in its camp in the\ngreat beyond; and we, of a later and\nlesser generation, will see his like no\nmore.\nRichmond. BRYAN CONRAD\nGARBER FORGERS\nTO FILE NOTICE\nG. O. P. Candidate For Congress\nIn Seventh Fails to Qualify\nIn Time Set By Law.\nCongressional political circles wer\u00a7\nsurprised by the failure of two Re\npublican candidates for Congress\u2014\nRepresentative J. A. Garber, of the\nSeventh district, candidate for re\nelection and M. J. Putnain, of the\nTenth district\u2014to file notices of\ntheir candidacy with the Secretary\nof Commonwealth in time set by law\nto get their names printed on the of\nficial ballots.\nUnder Virginia election laws all\ncandidates for State and Federal of\nfices must file notice of their candi\ndacy with the Secretary of the Com\nmonwealth sixty days prior to the\nelection. The time limit expired\nlast Friday midnight, and the failux-e\nof the two Republcan nominees to\nfile the notices means their support\ners either must wrife or stamp their\nnames on the ballots. This is ex\npected to mean the loss of several\nthousand votes for each candidate.\nSays He Simply Forgot.\nRepresentative Garber admitted\nthat the failure to file notice was an\noversight. He offered no excuse that\nhe did not know the law\u2019s provisions,\nas he filed his notice two years ago\nwhen he ran for Congress.\n\u201cJ simply forgot it; that is all,\u201d\nhe said. \u2018\u2018The matter slipped my\nmind entirely.\u201d\nJohn W. Fishburne of Charlottes\nville, nominated by the Democrats to\nredeem the lower valley district, said\nhe has no desire to take any advan\ntage of his opponent\u2019s negligence.\n\u2018\u2018It is not my responsibility to in\nterpret the election law involved in\nMr. Garber's failure to file his notice\nin the time fixed by the law,\u201d said\nFishburne, \u201cbut I am frank to say\nthat I hope the matter will be ad\njusted legally so that Mr. Garber\u2019s\nname can be printed on the official\nballot with mine. I have no desire\nto take any political advantage of a\nsituation of this kind, and I regret\nthat Mr. Garber overlooked the filing\nof his name. I filed my notice some\ntime ago as required by law.\u201d\nKecks to Remedy Situation.\nGarber went to Richmond Satur\nday to confer with Peter Saunders,\nSecretary of the Commonwealth, to\nascertain what he could do to get his\nname on the ballot. .As the situation\nstood at that time, Saunders held he\nwas controlled by the law and had no\npower to authorize the placing of\nGarber\u2019s name on the ballot. Gar\nber\u2019s recourse was said to be in the\ncourts, but whether he would appeal\nto them was not known.\n-The first of the week brought an\nupholding of Mr. Saunders\u2019 stand by\nthe Attorney General, so it was defi\nnite that Mr. Garber\u2019s name would\nnot be printed on the ballots.\nI The \u201cRambler\u201d in the Richmond\nNews-Leader: Most of us are sorry\ni that Mr. Garber forgot to file his no\ntice of candidacy in time, but most of\nus will admit that Virginia needs\ntii: Congressmen who do not forget\njJF-' -o\nf:. COLOR INFLUENCES SALE\nOF NEWLY BUILT HOUSE\nHome owners are demanding more\ncolor in houses of all types. The style\nappeal indicated by color is exerting\na stronger influence in the purchase\nof a home than do many a construc\nk features.\nThis was the opinion of Mr. F- H.\nMorris, local distributor of du Pont\npaints, varnishes and Duco.. He con\ni\u2019 tinued, \u201cThe popularity of many\nH types of architecture such as the\nEnglsb type for smal houses, is due.\nto a large extent to theopportunity\nfor more color. It is said that one\nof the things which lure families\ny from city apartment houess to the\nsuburbs is the more colorful effects\nwhich arc nnK\u00ab<ble ill a house.\u201d\nfc\" t\nBOYS MUST HAVE\nLICENSE TO HUNT\nPersons Under Sixteen Exempt\nFor Fishing Only In In\nland Waters.\nWith the hunting season on squir\nrel. dove, etc., comes the usual de\nbates and discussions among the\nsportsmen as to the privileges and\nrestrictions provided by the game\nlaws. Just the other day a discus\nsion arose whether a person under\nsixteen years of age must obtain a li\ncense to hunt. According to the new\nGame, Inland Fish and Dog Code the\nanswer is YES.\nIt those who are in doubt will\ncarefully study the following ex\ntract from the new Virginia Code,\nthey will find that the exemption\nfrom license to persons under six\nteen is for Ashing only in inland wat\ners, and not hunting, as many have\ninterpreted:\nInformation About Virginia Inland\nFish Laws.\nUnder the provisions of section 19\nof the new Game, Inland Fish and\nDog Code, it will be unlawful after\nJuly 1, 1930, to hunt, or to trap, ex\ncept with box or rabbit traps, or to\nfish in inland waters of this State,\nwith a rod and reel; or by any other\nmethod whereby artificial lures or\nlive minnows are used; or to fish for\nbrook or rainbow trout, without first\nobtaining a license, provided that\nsuch license shall not be required, as i\nfollows:\n(a) Of resident landowners, their\nhusbands or wives and their children:\nnonresident children of resident\nlandowners: nonresidents who own\nland in this State, their husbands or\nwives and their children; and unnat\nuralized persons who own land in\nthis^State and their children, to\nhunt, trap and fish within the bound\"\ndries of their own lands and inland\nwaters or to fish in inland waters\nbounding and adjoining their said I\nland. i\n(b) Of tenants, renters and less\nees to hunt, trap and fish within the\nboundaries of the lands and inland\nwaters of their landlords or to fish in\ninland waters bounding and adjoin\ning said land; provided that such\ntenant, renter or lessee actually re\nsides upon said land and has the\nwritten consent of the landlord to do\nso upon his person at the time.\n(c) Of persons under sixteen years\nof age to fish in inland waters.\nNothing above shall be construed\nas authorizing any person to hunt,\ntrap or fish upon the lands or in the\ninland waters of any public or pri\nvate gun club, association or pre\nserve of any description as a member\nthereof, or. as a landowner, tenant,\nrenter or lessee, without having pro\ncured a license. i\nInland Waters.\nSection 8 deilnes inland waters to\nmean and to include all waters above\ntidewater and the brackish and fresh\nwater streams, creeks, bays (includ\ning Back Bay), inlets and ponds ir\nthe tidewater counties. Under an\nopinion of the Attorney Generol of\nVirginia, date^ June 9,1930. it is\nheld t be unlawful to fish with rod\nand reel, or by any other method\nwhereby artificial lures, or bait, or\nlive minnows are used, or to fish for\nbrook or rainbow trout in any man\nner or by any means, without a li\ncense, with the exception of salt wa\ner in Tidewater Virginia.\nLicense.\nOne license covers hunting, trap\nping and fishing. County license to\na resident, $1.00; Statewide license\nto a resident $3.00; Statewide license\nto a nonresident, $15.50; and State\nwide license to fish only, to a non\nresident, $5.00.\n-O-\nPULLIAM BATS FOURTH\nWITH PARK AGGREGATION\nAccording to figures released this\nweek by the Winchester Park Base\nball Association, Mat Pulliam of Ber\nryville, prominent in the line-up on\nthe Frederick team the later part of\nthis season, is rated fourth to the\nhighest baiting average of those in\nthe aggregation. Mat\u2019s average was\n.387, the highest being .476.\nIn the season of 1928-29, Pulliam\nwas Berryville High School\u2019s stellar\nplayer, pitching his school to victory\nin quite a number of games, among\nthem the Clarke-Frederick league\nbattles, in which the banner was car\nried off by the locals He also held\nthe mound for the Berryville town\nteam in a number of its contests that\nyear,and chalked up several wins for\nthe Richmond Medical College\nwhile atending that institution the\npast spring.\n\u25a0o\nBOYCE NOTES\nMrs. F. G. Carper of McLean spent\nSaturday and Sunday with her sis\nter, Mrs. M. Royston.\nMisses Eva Massey and Doris Reid\nJolliffe are spending a week at Roan\noke with relatives.\nMr. E. Hopkins McLaughlin of\nRichmond spent the weekend at\n\"Roseville\u201d, the home of Mr. and\nMrs. Alex Jolliffe.\nMisses Jane and Frances Jolliffe\nleft Monday for Williamsburg and\nMiddletown, Va., respectively, the\nformer to resume her studies at Wil\nliam and Mary College and the latter\nbeing a teacher in the Middletown\nHigh School this session.\nMr. and, Mrs. J. L. Carper and\nMrs Alex Jolliffe visited Mrs. E. T.\nBarr at Stephens City on Monday\nwho is confined to her home .ttyere\nwith a very painful attack ot neuri\ntis.\n--O- i\nSTOVE FOR SALE\nLarge coal stove. Will burn hard\nor soft coal. In good condition. Ap\nPly MISS ETHEL COOPER, Boyce,\n9-11 tf Va.\nPERSONALS\n\nMr. and Mrs. Robert H. Thomas\nand son Robert of Mission' Home, Va.\nhave been visiting Mr6. Thomas\u2019\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. VV. M. Hardes\nty for the past three weeks.\nMr. and Mrs. Fred Hardesty gnd\ndaughter Betty Ann of Akron, Ohio,\nwere guests last week of Mr. Har\ndesty\u2019s mother, Mrs. Bettie Hardesty.\nMrs. Tyson Dortch returned Satur\nday frm Toronto where she went with\nMajor Dortch who attended the North\nAmerican Gasoline Tax Conference\nheld there last week.\nDr. Wells A. Daniels has returned\nafter spending several weeks with\nMrs. Daniels, who is visiting her\nparents. Mr. and Mrs. George Woods\nat Naragansett, R. I. Mrs Daniels\nwill return to Berryville in October.\nMiss Louise Harris has returned\nfrom Durham, N. C., where she\nspent several months\nMr. and Mrs. Percy Crown who\nhave been visiting their sister. Miss\nSarah B. Crown at \u201cWoodlawn\u201d,\nhave returned to Columbia, S. C.\nThey were acompanied by Miss Fair\nfax Meade who will spend a few days\nin Columbia before returing to\nNew- York by boat from Charleston.\nMrs. J. T. L. Jones has rptnrnpri\nfrom Washington where she spent a\nfew days with friends.\nMr. and Mrs. Walter D. Wisecarv\ner and their daughter, Mrs Nicholas\nMorrison, spent the week end at\nBaltimore.\nMiss Fannie Fenton is spending a\nweek at Washington.\nMrs. Tessier of Richmond is the\nguest of her sister. Mrs. Blackburn\nSmith, at \u201cThe Knoll\u201d.\nMrs. Frank Dovel has returned to\nBaltimore after visiting at the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. J. Ed. Ogden\nMr and Mrs. A C Muller spent the\nweek end at Columbia, Va\nMrs. Nicodemus of Baltimore is\nthe guest of Mr. and Mrs. Charles H.\nPhillips I\nGuests at the home of Mr. and\nMrs. Lacy Broy included Mr. and\nMrfe John Stickles and son, John, Jr.\nof Sumit Point, Misses Anna Brov\nand Katherine Lake of Berryville.\nMr. and Mrs. Jared McDonald and\nson Malcolm of near Berryville, Mr.\nand Mrs Noah Carroll and daughter\nGladys of Boyce, and Mr and Mrs. 1\nEdw. Locke and daughter Dorothy of\nBriggs. j\nMr .and Mrs. Herbert Whiting mo- I\ntored to Washington on Wednesday.\nMr .Harris Smith of Cottage Ter- j\nrace, Md., and Charles Town, W. Va j\nwas a visitor at the home of Mr and\nMrs. J A. Stolle this week.\nMessrs Douglas and William Car- j\nter are spending the latter pat of the\nweek in Washington\n--O--\nFOR SALE\nSmall house in good repair. Nice!\nsized lot and garden. Located on I\nRice Street. Priced to sell. Easy\nterms. Owned by Miss Rose More\n'pUBJ\nRALPH X. DORSEY V j\nReal Estate\ni\nBerryville, Va.\nTHE MIND IN MOTION\n\"In peace cti well as in war the\nmint! mwJt be kept in motion.\"\n170,000 BOOKS AT ('ALL\n^What remedy can be suggested for\nthe deplorable lack of libraries in\nVirginia? There are 63 public and\nsemi-public libraries in the State\nwhich, excluding the ten largest,\naverage fewer than 3000 volumes in\nsize. Only four per cent of our ru\nral population has access to books.\nIf Virginia had delierately set out,\none investigator has stated, to pre\nvent the spread of books -through\nthe rural sections, the situation could\nhardly be worse than it is now.\nAgainst the time when true county\nlibraries with Branches in schools,\nvillage postoffices and crossroads\nstores,'are set up, loans by mail from\ncentral libraries are the only solu\ntion. Already this local service,\nbacked by a lending library with\n170,000 books, is bringing pleasure\nto many who have disc vered that\nthe reading material they want is as\nnear as their mailbox.\nReaders of The Courier may obtaih\nwithout charge an explanation of how\nhundreds of the best and newest\nbooks are distributed far and wide,\nby sending this notice or a postal\ncard request to the Extension De\npartment, University, Virginia.\n-:-0\nMRS. TILFORD HOSTESS\nTO THE GARDEN CLUB\nLast week Mrs. Frank V. Tilford\nwas hostess to the Winchester and\nClarke Ciun^y Garden Club at her\nbeautiful colonial home, \u201cMilton\nValley\u201d. Mrs. E. G. Butler of Mill\nwood, in the asence of the president,\nMrs. Melvin Green- of Winchester,\npresided\nMrs. Thomas S. Wheelwright of\nBuckhead Springs, Va., was the guest\nof honor and gave an interesting\ntalk on the conservation and propa\ngation of holly, the most romantic j\nof evergreens, 500 carloads of which\nwere s-ent out of the State last year.\nTJje chairman of the flower show\ncommittee advised that on account\nof the drought \u2019and scarcity of flow\ners the show be postponed from\nSeptember 26 to next spring. The\nmotion was carried.\nMrs. Joseph A. Masr-ie will be the\nhostess of the Club when it meets at I\nWinchester bn September 17.\n-O\n15-YEAR GOITRE REMOVED\nV\u00ab. Lady Tells How In Letter Re\nceived Here.\nMrs. O. L. Shelton, Whittles Depot\nVn., has written a letter to Harris'\nPharmacy telling how easily she re\nmoved her goitre at home without\npain or knife. How severe choking\ndifficult breathing, throbbing, head- j\naches, nervousness and sleeplessness\nwere releived. Mrs. Shelton har\nnothing to sell. You are welcome to\ncall and read her letter r\u2014Adv\n-0-*\nMr. and Mrs. Ed Ziler of Cumber\nland, Md., have been visiting rela\ntives here.\nTT'HERE is a tremendous amount of\nsatisfaction an being able to offer\nv\nfarmers in this vicinity the newModel\u201cL\u201dCase\nTractor. Those who have seen it pronounce it\nyears ahead of present-day tractors because\nit has all the best features of modern design\nplus addition::! features as well.\nNow see what you think of the new Case.\nIts great power Will astonish you, especially\nwhen you consider that the tractor weighs but\nslightly more than three draft horses. Its ease\nof handling, its three forward speeds, its short\nturning radius, its accessibility of all parts, its\nroomy platform, its adjustable spring scat\nall these features and many more will instantly\nappeal toyou.\nWhether or not you are in immediate need\nof a tractor, it will pay you to investigate the\nnew Case. Come in and get a copy of our new\nbooklet that shows this attractive tractor in.\n'its natural blue-gray and ted colors.\nt\u00bbi. mu\nG. J. LONGERBEAM\nBerry ville Virginia\nW vvi h;\u2022 ''.k: r ?'/f m\nFEW DEEDS RECORDED\nHERE IN RECENT PAST\nVery few transfers of real estate\nhave been admitted to record in the\nCounty Clerk\u2019s office during the past\nseveral weeks. Among the deedo re\ncently recorded are:\nBy date of August 9, Lloyd Wil\nliams Post No. 41, the American Le\ngion, to Roy E. Potts\u2014dwelling and\nparcel of land on corner of Main\nStreet and Buckmarsh Street (the\nCharles Town pike).\nW. S. Dix and wife to Nellie Hen\nson\u2014lot adjoining the Dix property,\nBerryville.\nDated September 6, W. Cabell\nMoore \"and Joseph P. Moore, exeeu\ntors qf A. Moore, Jr., deceased, to\nAnnie B. C. Moore and Elvira Wil\nliams\u2014lot in the Moore plat in the\nnortheastern section of Berryville.\nWARDEN AND ASSOCIATES\nBUT BERKELEY SPRINGS PLANT\nThe Berkeley Springs Ice and Cold\nStorage Company, formerly the Mor\ngan County Cold Storage Company\nlocated at Berkeley Springs, W. Va.\u2019\nhas just recently beem purchsed b\u00bb\nMessrs. H. C Warden, Berryville:\nJ Ashby Sprint, Winchester, and J p\nWilson, Martinsburg. Mr. Warden\nis president, -Mr. Sprint, vice-presi\ndent, and Mr. Wilson, secretary and\ntreasurer of the company\nIt has a capacity of 65,000 barrels\nand the officials anonunce that it i*\nnow ready to receive apple shipments\nfor cold storage.\n-O\nMiss Isabelle Carper of Berryvllle\nhas gone to Richmond and Norfolk\nfor a few days\u2019 visit.\nMr. and Mrs. W, E. Henson and\nson Billie accompanied Miss Isabella\nCarper as far as Washington and\nspent the day there\nTEN YEARS AGO\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK was poor\nthe markets were erratic and unemploy\nment was on the increase. At that time\nour advice was to avoid becoming pani\ncky, to work and to save, looking forward\nto the inevitable readjustment that must\nfollow.\nTODAY our advice is the same.\nTHE\nFirst National Bank\nof Berryville.\nCONSULT US ABOUT YOUR\nBUILDING MATERIALS\nYellow Pine and Fir Framing and Sheathing\nPine and Fir Flooring Rift and Flat\nLong Bell Oak Flooring\nHigh Grade Finish Lumber\nU. S. Gypsum Plaster and Stucco\nMorgan Millwork\nWeather Best Stained Shingles\nJohns Manville Roofing Rigid Asbestos\nand Flexible Asphalt 1\nSand and Stone\nLehigh and Atlas Portland Cement\nRussell and Erwin Hardware\ndu Pont Paints and Varnishes\nWe shall be glad to give you an estimate\non your work\n\nJohn W. Rosenberger Company\nPhone 72 Winchester, Virginia\n^Convenience\nFor Sale\nr\n1 OR you.... for your friends... for your\nguests... for anyone who conies to your\nhouse.\nI\nA telephone installed in your home means\ntime, energy and steps saved\u2014in\na word, CONVENIENCE\nand all for just a few cents\na day.\nTHE CHESAPEAKE AND POTOMAC TELEPHONE COMPANY\n_ OF VIRCHMIA","height":"30024","width":"20808"}}
